  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "https://github.com/trufflesuite/truffle/blob/e0c903d47cf52f10da74fd0348f8bdb2ef973818/packages/db/test/arbitraries/networks.ts#L89\r\n\r\nMaybe a non-issue, but when using these arbitraries in some ganache tests I ran into an issue when comparing block hashes. Ganache stores them in its db \"compacted\" (leading 0s removed) and when pulled back out they have leading 0s restored based on a fixed width of 32 _bytes_. So a hash like `0x0012345678901234` (as generated by the arbitraries) gets stored as `Buffer.from([12, 34, 56, 78, 90, 12, 34, 05])` and when read from the DB later and turned back into a string it will become: `0x00000000000000000012345678901234` (32 _bytes_).\r\n\r\nMaybe ganache shouldn't assume all block hashes will be 32 bytes, or maybe the `Hash` arbitrary should require specifying the byte size of the generated hash, i.e.:\r\n\r\n```typescript\r\nconst Hash = (byteSize: number): fc.Arbitrary<string> =>\r\n  fc\r\n    .hexaString({\r\n      minLength: byteSize * 2,\r\n      maxLength: byteSize * 2\r\n    })\r\n    .map(hash => `0x${hash}`);\r\n```\r\n\r\n/shrug",
